Ignore please.

KSP 1.3.1 - Module Manager 2.8.0.dll disables stock Mk2-R Radial-Mount Parachute.

This is... funky. Using MM with no other mods causes the radial parachute to fail to appear as a parachute. It doesn't appear in the staging lists, nor to the engineering report, nor can it be deployed by right-clicking.

To recreate:

  1. Brand-new KSP 1.3.1 install.
  2. Drag ModuleManager.2.8.0.dll into GameData - not other mods needed!
  3. Start new sandbox game.
  4. Enter VAB and choose a module - I was using the Mk 1.2 capsule.
  5. Choose the above radial parachute and attach it to the capsule: the parachute fails to appear in the staging list.
  6. Confirm that the Engineering report believes there to be no parachutes.
  7. Launch capsule, and confirm that parachute isn't in staging list, nor can it be deployed by right-clicking.

Save and log file HERE

OK, so I failed to completely stockify my install.

1 hour ago, PyjackMeat said:

Okay, what have I ballsed up here?

RESOURCE nodes contain 'name', 'amount' and 'maxAmount' not 'resourceName' and 'ratio' (those look more like INPUT_RESOURCE and OUTPUT_RESOURCE from inside a converter module).

You need to calculate how much each unit of supplies should be equivalent to in Food, Water, Oxygen etc. then you can do something like this (not tested):

Spoiler 

@PART[...]:NEEDS[...]
{
    // put your conversion factors here
    foodFactor = 1 
    waterFactor = 1
    oxygenFactor = 1
    wasteFactor = 1
    wasteWaterFactor = 1
    carbonDioxideFactor = 1
    
    amountSupplies = #$/RESOURCE[Supplies]/maxAmount$
    
    RESOURCE
    {
        name = Food
        
        amount = #$/amountSupplies$
        @amount *= #$/foodFactor$ 
        
        maxAmount = #$/amountSupplies$
        @maxAmount *= #$/foodFactor$ 
    }
    
    // do the same for water, oxygen, waste etc.
    
}

@PART[...]:NEEDS[...]
{
    // clean up
    !RESOURCE[Supplies] {}
    !RESOURCE[Mulch] {}
    
    !amountSupplies = delete
    
    !foodFactor = delete
    !waterFactor = delete
    !oxygenFactor = delete
    !wasteFactor = delete
    !wasteWaterFactor = delete
    !carbonDioxideFactor = delete
}

How do I find nodes that do not have a name field defined?

I want to add a field to the PART node depending on what model is defined, but the MODEL node is defined by "model = ...", not " name = ...".

This is my best guess, but it doesn't work. 

//Apply "Test1 = 1" to all parts that do NOT have model = SSTU/Assets/EmptyProxyModel
@PART[*]:HAS[@MODEL[~model[SSTU/Assets/EmptyProxyModel]]]
{
	%Test1 = 1
}

18 minutes ago, Nightside said:

How do I find nodes that do not have a name field defined?

I want to add a field to the PART node depending on what model is defined, but the MODEL node is defined by "model = ...", not " name = ...".

 

You need an extra HAS after the node name: 

@PART[*]:HAS[@MODEL:HAS[~model[SSTU/Assets/EmptyProxyModel]]]
{
	%Test1 = 1
}

NOTE: You'll need a different filter to catch parts that don't have any MODEL node at all

1 hour ago, linuxgurugamer said:

I'm trying to delete a value if one of three modules exists: 


@PART[*]:HAS[@MODULE[IFI_Extreme]|@MODULE[IFI_Improved]|@MODULE[IFI_Advanced]]:FINAL
{
	!IFI_Tech = none
}

The lack of OR in HAS requires a bit of a work around. For example: 

// mark things we don't want to patch
@PART[*]:HAS[!MODULE[IFI_Extreme],!MODULE[IFI_Improved],!MODULE[IFI_Advanced]]
{
	IFIModuleFound = true
}

// do the patch
@PART[*]:HAS[~IFIModuleFound[]]
{
	!IFI_Tech = none
}

// remove marker
@PART[*]
{
	!IFIModuleFound = delete
}

Relies on the fact that A OR B OR C is the same as NOT(NOT(A) AND NOT(B) AND NOT(C))
